[White "Chapter 1"]
[Black "3...de4 4.f3?! Dubious gambit"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B15"]
[Annotator "GM Burak Firat"]
[PlyCount "20"]
[EventDate "2018.10.25"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. f3 $6 {This line is rare. You may not face it
in a classical game, but when you do, it's better to be prepared.} exf3 {
Black should certainly accept the challenge.} 5. Nxf3 {With this sacrifice
White aims to get the initiative early in the game. He has already developed
two minor pieces and opened the f-file for his rook. But with correct play,
Black doesn't need to worry. I believe this line is dubious. In order to
justify his pawn sacrifice, White needs to follow-up very energetically. But
against correct play, his chances to do this are very limited.} (5. Qxf3 $2 {
Sacrificing the second pawn is not a good idea.} Qxd4 $1 {In this position
Black can afford being greedy.} 6. Be3 (6. Bd2 $146 {This might be a better
try. But still White is not ready to castle long because Black has ...Bg4.} Nf6
$17) 6... Qb4 $19 {White is not able to castle long because of ...Bg4.}) 5...
Bf5 $5 {The main moves are ...Nf6 and ...Bg4. But I don't see anything wrong
with ... Bf5 either. As we know, one of the main ideas in the Caro-Kann is to
develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn-chain.} 6. Bc4 (6. Ne5 $6 e6
7. Bf4 (7. g4 $2 Qh4+ 8. Kd2 Qf2+ 9. Ne2 Be4 $19) 7... Nd7 $17 {It's in
Black's interest to exchange pieces.}) (6. Be2 {This is not how White should
play after sacrificing a pawn, as the Bishop isn't very active here.} e6 7. O-O
Nf6 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Nh4 Bg6 $146 10. Qd2 Nbd7 $17 {next will be 0-0. Black is a
full pawn up.}) (6. Nh4 Be6 $1 $146 (6... e6 $6 {This move allows White to
open the position for his pieces.} 7. Nxf5 exf5 8. Bc4 $1 $146 {White has good
attacking chances.}) 7. Bf4 Nf6 8. Qd2 g6 9. O-O-O Bg7 $17 {White's
compensation is insufficient. Black has a safe king, and he can look for
counterplay on the queenside.}) (6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Nf6 8. Bg5 e6 9. O-O (9.
Bxf6 gxf6 $1 10. O-O-O Nd7 $17 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gf8e7,Ge8c8] Black's idea is very
simple. After castling queenside, his king will be safe.}) (9. O-O-O Nbd7 $146
10. Kb1 Be7 $17 {Now Black can castle either way, with the better position.})
9... Nbd7 10. Ne4 Be7 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. Ne5 h6 {[%cal Re4g5,Rf1f6,Rd3h7]
preparing to castle.} 13. Rae1 O-O $17 {Black is simply pawn up. He can aim
for piece exchanges and a well-times c6-c5.}) (6. Bg5 $146 {I was wondering
how Black should react after this move, which hasn't been played yet.} Nf6 $1 {
There is nothing wrong with the doubled f-pawns.} 7. Bxf6 exf6 $17) 6... e6 7.
O-O (7. Qe2 Be7 8. O-O Nf6 9. Bf4 O-O $17 {I am not going into detail from
here. Black has an extra pawn and a comfortable position. I don't see any
compensation for White.}) 7... Nf6 8. Ne5 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Re5f7,Rf1f5] White
threatens to take on f7. This is a well-known motif in this variation. Black
should be careful about this.} (8. Bg5 Be7 9. Qe2 O-O 10. Rad1 Nbd7 $17) (8.
Ng5 {White is threatening to take on f7 and f5.} Bg6 9. Ne2 (9. Bxe6 $2 fxe6
10. Nxe6 Qd7 11. Re1 (11. Bg5 $146 Qxe6 $1 12. Bxf6 (12. Re1 Ne4 13. Qf3 Nxg5
14. Qg4 Kd8 $1 15. Rxe6 Nxe6 16. Qxe6 Nd7 $19) 12... Kd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c8]
Black's king will be safe on c8.}) 11... Kf7 {There is no compensation left
for White. Black's king will be safe on g8.}) 9... Bd6 $1 {[%cal Re2f4,Yd6f4]
Black is ready to eliminate White's activity by exchanging pieces.} 10. Nf4
Bxf4 11. Bxf4 Nd5 $17 {Black solved all of his problems and soon will be able
to castle short. Actually instead of 11...Nd5 it was also possible to play 0-0
right away. Both options give him the advantage.}) 8... Bg6 $1 {[%csl Gf7,Gg6]
Black protects his f7 pawn and defends against the threat Rf5.} 9. Bg5 (9. Be3
Nbd7 10. Qe2 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 $17 {No reason to be afraid of the rook on the
open f-file. The bishop on g6 is perfectly placed to protect f7.}) (9. g4 Bd6
10. Bf4 Bxe5 11. Bxe5 Nbd7 $17 {[%cal Re5d6,Gd7b6]}) 9... Be7 10. Kh1 Nbd7 $17
{Black is ready to complete his development in a few moves, with a solid
position and a healthy extra pawn. I don't see any real attacking chances for
White.} *

