1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Bd3 $5 (5. Qd3 {I played this
move myself to go out of theory. The main idea is to prevent ...Bf5.} Qd5 $5 {
This is a nice idea used by David Alberto in his game against me. Black puts
immediate pressure on white's knight. After an exchange on f6 the white queen
on d3 stands worse than black's on d5.} (5... Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Nd7 7. Nf3 Nf6 8.
Qd3 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Rd3f5] This occurred in a game that I lost against
Melkumyan,Hrant, but the opening part was a success for me. Black's natural
continuation would be ...g6 in order to enable ...Bf5. But in this position,
the bishop is not well-placed on g7, as it doesn't support c6-c5.}) (5... e5 $2
{Most readers will probably know this nice game, but not the fact that it
originated from this very opening line.} 6. dxe5 Qa5+ 7. Bd2 Qxe5 8. O-O-O Nxe4
9. Qd8+ Kxd8 10. Bg5+ Kc7 11. Bd8# {Reti-Tartakower 1910 / 1-0}) 6. Nc3 Qa5 {
I was not happy about my position during the game, but didn't want to take on
f6, which leads to a bad version of 5.Nxf6+. This position is similar to the
because it doesn't belong to the Scandinavian Defense: 1. e4 d5 2.exd5 Qxd5 3.
Nc3 Qa5 4.d4 Nf6. Obviously the insertion of Qd3 and c7-c6 favours Black.} 7.
Bd2 Bf5 $1 (7... Na6 8. Ne4 Qd5 9. Nxf6+ exf6 10. c4 Qe6+ 11. Be2 Bd6 {This
was play in my game against David,A. Now White's best chance was} 12. Nf3 $1
$146 O-O 13. O-O Nb4 14. Qe3 Qxe3 15. fxe3 $1 $14 {, with the slightly better
chances in this queenless middlegame.}) 8. Qg3 (8. Ne4 $6 Qd5 $1 9. Nxf6+ gxf6
$1 $15 {White doesn't have a good square for his queen.}) 8... e6 $146 9. Nf3 (
9. O-O-O $2 b5 $1 $17 {Black's attack is very fast here.}) 9... Na6 $1 {
[%cal Ga6b4] Black has no problems. To illustrate, I will just show one
variation:} 10. Rc1 Nb4 11. a3 Nbd5 $5 {Easiest.} (11... Nxc2+ {leads to
unnecessary complications after Rc2 or Kd1.}) 12. Nxd5 (12. Ne5 Nxc3 13. Bxc3
Qd8 {Black is OK. Generally any piece on c3 is bad, as it blocks the c-pawn.})
12... Qxd5 13. Qc7 (13. c4 Qd8 $11 {[%cal Gf6e4]}) 13... Bd6 (13... Qd7 {
is also possible.} 14. Qxd7+ Nxd7 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Yh7h6] is
around equal.}) 14. Qxb7 O-O $44 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gf8b8,Yd5a2,Ga8b8] Black has
at least enough compensation for the pawn.}) 5... Qxd4 6. Nf3 (6. Be3 $2 {
This is too much.} Qxb2 $1 $146 7. Rb1 Qxa2 8. Nxf6+ exf6 $19) (6. Nxf6+ $2
Qxf6 7. Nf3 Bg4 $17) (6. Ne2 $6 {This way of development slows down White's
initiative.} Qd8 7. N2g3 Nxe4 8. Nxe4 g6 $5 $146 {[%csl Gd6,Ge7][%cal Gf8g7,
Ge7d6] With the pawn staying on e7, Black keeps control of the square d6 and
an unblocked bishop on c8.} 9. h4 Bf5 10. Qe2 Bg7 11. h5 Qc7 $15 {[%cal Gb8d7,
Gd7e5,Yd7b6,Ge8c8]}) (6. Qe2 Nxe4 7. Bxe4 Nd7 8. Nf3 Qc5 $146 {[%cal Gd7f6,
Gc8f5]} 9. O-O Nf6 10. Bd3 Bf5 11. Be3 Qa5 12. b4 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Qc7 14. b5 e6
15. bxc6 Qxc6 16. Rfd1 (16. Ne5 Qd5 $17) 16... Be7 17. Ne5 Qa4 $17 {[%csl Ga4]
[%cal Rd3b5]}) 6... Qd8 7. Qe2 (7. O-O $2 {A pawn down White should not allow
Black to exchange queens.} Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 f6 10. Nd4 e5 11. Nf5 g6
12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. Rxd6 Ke7 $17) (7. Neg5 {[%cal Rg5f7,Rd3g6,Rf3e5]} Qc7 8. O-O
h6 $1 $146 9. Nxf7 (9. Ne4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 e5 11. Re1 Be6 $17 {[%cal Gb8d7]})
9... Kxf7 10. Re1 Kg8 $1 11. Ne5 Be6 12. Bf4 Qc8 13. Qe2 Nbd7 14. Ng6 Bf7 $17 {
[%csl Rg6][%cal Gc8e8] White won't be able to support his knight on g6. After
it is evicted, Black simply has an extra piece.}) (7. Nxf6+ exf6 8. Qe2+ Be6
$146 9. Bc4 (9. O-O Bc5 10. Bc4 Qe7 11. Re1 Nd7 12. Bf4 Nb6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14.
Qxe6 Qxe6 15. Rxe6+ Kf7 16. Rae1 Rhe8 17. Rxe8 Rxe8 18. Rxe8 Kxe8 $11) 9... Bc5
10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Qxe6+ Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {with equality.}) 7... Bf5 $5 $146 {
I prefer this move, as it is easier to play than 7...Nxe4.} (7... Nxe4 8. Qxe4
(8. Bxe4 g6 {We have already seen this idea in chapter 1.} 9. O-O Bg7 10. c3
O-O 11. Bf4 Nd7 $17 {[%cal Ge7e5]}) 8... Nd7 9. Be3 $1 $146 {[%cal Rd7c5]
White should try to slow down Black's development. Otherwise it will be easy
for Black to develop and keep his extra pawn.} (9. Qh4 Nc5 $1 $146 10. Bc4 Bf5
$17 {[%cal Ge7e6]}) 9... Nf6 10. Qa4 $1 e6 11. O-O {White has compensation.})
8. Nxf6+ (8. O-O Bxe4 $1 9. Bxe4 Nbd7 10. Bf4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Nf6 12. Qe2 e6 13.
Rad1 Qa5 14. Rd3 $1 Be7 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd3b3]} 15. Rb3 $1 {White's
compensation is at best enough for equality.}) 8... gxf6 9. Bxf5 Qa5+ 10. Bd2
Qxf5 11. O-O-O Nd7 12. Kb1 Qb5 $5 $44 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8e7,Ge8c8,Gh8g8] White
has some compensation, but Black shouldn't have any problems.} *

