1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Ng3 {Enjoying more space, White
prefers to keep all pieces on the board. But generally the g3 square is not a
good place for the knight in this pawn structure. As this analysis shows, it
will not be able to move forward. That's why in the Caro-Kann there are many
lines in which White plays Ne4 back, to exchange it for the black knight on f6.
} (5. Ng5 {This move is in the spirit of the 3...Nd7 line: 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.
Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Ng5. But with the king's knight on f6 instead of the
queen's knight on d7, Black can attack the white centre right away.} c5 $5 (
5... h6 {only helps White after} 6. N5f3 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gg1f3]}) 6. Bc4 e6 7. Ne2
(7. Be3 Qa5+ $5 $146 8. c3 cxd4 9. Qxd4 Nc6 10. Qf4 Ne5 11. N1f3 (11. Be2 $6
Ng6 $1 (11... Ba3 $5 12. Bc1 Be7 $15) 12. Qd4 Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] Black has an
excellent version of the French Rubinstein.}) 11... Nxc4 12. Qxc4 Be7 $15 {
Black has the better position thanks to his bishop pair.}) 7... Nc6 8. Nf3 a6
9. a4 b6 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc8b7]} (9... Na5 {is equally good. Either way Black
doesn't have any problems:} 10. Ba2 b5 11. Bg5 c4 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Gc8b7,Gf8e7]
})) 5... h5 {Immediately playing against the knight on g3.} (5... c5 $5 {
is an interesting alternative:} 6. Nf3 (6. dxc5 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 e6 8. Bb5+ (8. b4
a5 9. c3 axb4 $146 10. cxb4 Bd7 {Controlling White's queenside majority on the
light squares, Black has good compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) (8. Be3
Ng4 $146 9. Ne4 Nxe3+ 10. fxe3 Nd7 11. Nd6+ Ke7 $5 12. b4 a5 13. a3 g6 {
Against Black has good compensation, as he is ahead in development and soon
exerting pressure on the dark squares.}) 8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. c6 bxc6
11. Nf3 a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Grabbing space on the queenside. Depending on
White's reaction Black can develop his bishop to g7, d6 or c5. The position is
equal.}) (6. Bb5+ Nbd7 7. a4 a6 $146 8. Be2 e6 9. Nf3 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] Again
this is a good version of the French Rubinstein.}) (6. Be3 cxd4 7. Bxd4 (7.
Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Bxd4 Nc6 9. Bb5 Bd7 {Black is more than okay.}) 7... Nc6 {, and
Black is already slightly preferable.}) 6... Nc6 (6... Bg4 $6 {Unfortunately
this move from the main line 5...h5 doesn't work so well here due to} 7. h3 $1
Bxf3 8. Qxf3 $14) 7. Be3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 {Again Black shouldn't have any
problems.}) 6. h4 {This gives Black control over the g4 square. But other
moves do not promise White an advantage either.} (6. Nf3 h4 7. Ne2 Bg4 8. Ne5 (
8. Ng5 e6 9. c3 (9. h3 $146 Bf5 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black is okay.}) 9... c5 $1 $146
10. h3 Bf5 11. Qb3 Qb6 $15 {Black is better developed.}) (8. Nc3 Bxf3 9. gxf3 (
9. Qxf3 $146 Qxd4 {After ...Bg4 and ...Bxf3 it's consistent to accept the
challenge.} 10. Be2 e6 11. Be3 Qe5 $1 12. O-O-O Nbd7 {White's compensation is
sufficient for equality at best.}) 9... e6 $15 {Black is strategically better.}
) 8... Bf5 $146 {In the game Black played 8...Bh5, but this doesn't feel safe
to me. At some point White might be able to play Nf4 and seriously disturb
Black's coordination.} 9. Nc3 e6 {[%cal Gb8d7] Black is okay.}) (6. h3 $5 c5 7.
Nf3 $146 (7. c3 $6 cxd4 8. cxd4 Nc6 $146 9. Nf3 Be6 $15 {[%cal Ge6d5,Yh5h4,
Ye7e6]}) 7... Nc6 (7... cxd4 8. Qxd4 Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. Nb5 Na6 11. Bd3 e6
12. O-O Rd8 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ya6c5,Yf8e7] Black is okay.}) 8. Be3 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Qa5+
10. c3 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 e5 {Black is okay.}) (6. Bc4 h4 7. N3e2 Bf5 8. c3 e6 9.
Bd3 (9. h3 $6 Be4 $1 {A very nice idea by Nisipeanu.} 10. f3 Bf5 $15) 9... Bxd3
10. Qxd3 Nbd7 $11 {Black has no problems.}) 6... c5 $5 {A very rare move. I am
sure it will be a surprise for any opponent.} 7. Nf3 (7. dxc5 Qxd1+ $146 8.
Kxd1 e6 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 11. c6 bxc6 12. c3 Bd6 $5 {Disturbing the
knight on g3.} 13. N1e2 Bc5 14. f3 Ne5 $13 {White's slightly better pawn
structure is counterbalanced by Black's active pieces.}) 7... Bg4 $5 $146 {
Exploiting the weakness that was created by 6.h4.} 8. c3 cxd4 9. Qxd4 Nc6 10.
Bb5 Bxf3 11. Qxd8+ Rxd8 12. gxf3 e6 {Thanks to his superior pawn structure,
only Black can be better.} *

