1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 {The doubled f-pawns
can be a liability in the endgame, as Black is now unable to create a passed
pawn from his kingside majority. On the other hand Black gains space to
quickly develop his minor and major pieces and good control over the central
squares d5, e6 and e5. The latter is the reason why White usually avoids Nf3
and prefers Ne2-g3, with further options to move to e4, f5 or h5.} 6. Be3 (6.
Ne2 {Blocking the bishop looks awkward. It's probably better to start with c3
and follow-up Bd3, Ne2. This is the main line, with the abovementioned idea.
The great Jan Timman employed it in 1980.} Bd6 7. Ng3 (7. Nc3 {This looks
strange to me. In general c3 is not a good placement for the Knight,
especially with a pawn on c2.} O-O 8. Bd3 f5 {[%cal Gd8h4,Re1g1] Taking
control of the e4-square and making castling difficult for White. Black
already has a pleasant position.} 9. Qf3 (9. O-O $146 Qh4 $1 10. g3 Qxd4 11.
Bxf5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bxf5 13. Rxd6 Bxc2 $15 {Black is pawn up.}) 9... Re8+ 10.
Kf1 (10. Ne2 $146 {Probably the lesser evil.} c5 $5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. O-O Nc6
$36 {Black has good piece play and the initiative. The position is a long way
from an endgame in which White's structural advantage would matter.}) 10... Qb6
$1 $146 {It's not easy for White to protect d4.} 11. Bxf5 Qxd4 12. Bxc8 (12.
Be3 Qc4+ $1 (12... Qf6 $2 13. Ne4 $1 $16) 13. Bd3 Qh4 $15 {White has
difficulties getting his king to safety and connecting his rooks.}) 12... Qc4+
$1 13. Qd3 Qxd3+ 14. cxd3 Rxc8 $15 {Now Black has the better structure in the
endgame.}) (7. g3 {This is not a bad way of development for the White bishop
on f1. But it takes away the g3-square from the knight.} O-O 8. Bg2 Re8 9. O-O
(9. Be3 Bg4 10. h3 {This move weakens White's position. In the future White
needs to take care of tactics involving Bxg3.} Bh5 11. Qd2 (11. O-O $2 $146
Bxg3 $17) 11... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6]} 12. b3 $6 (12. O-O $6 $146 Nb6 13. b3 Nd5
$15 {Black has very good position.}) (12. c4 $5 $146 Qe7 $5 {[%csl Rd4,Re3]
[%cal Ga8d8,Gd6b4,Yh5e2,Yd6g3]} 13. c5 Bc7 14. O-O Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Bxg3 16. fxg3
Qxe3+ 17. Qxe3 Rxe3 18. Kf2 {White probably has enough compensation for the
pawn here. His idea is b4-b5 or a well-timed d4- d5.}) 12... Qe7 $146 {[%cal
Yf6f5,Yd7f6,Yf6e4,Ga8d8,Gd7b6,Gb6d5] Black seems to be slightly better.}) 9...
Bg4 10. Re1 (10. f3 $6 {This is not a good move. White blocks his bishop g2
and weakens the e3 square.} Bf5 11. g4 Be6 12. b3 c5 $1 $146 {[%cal Gb8c6,
Yd4d5,Ye6d5] Black has the better position.}) (10. Be3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb6d5,
Yd7f8,Yf8e6]} 11. Qd3 Nf8 $146 12. c4 Qd7 {, and the position is about equal.})
10... Nd7 11. h3 Bh5 12. Be3 $2 {This following trick was mentioned earlier.}
Bxg3 $1 {0-1 (30) Nadj Hedjesi,B (2354)-Miladinovic,I (2566) Valjevo 2011}) (7.
Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 Re8 9. O-O-O Be6 $1 $146 10. Kb1 b5 $15 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4,
Yb8d7,Yd7b6] Black has good attacking chances.}) (7. Bf4 O-O 8. Qd2 (8. Bxd6
Qxd6 9. Qd2 Na6 $146 {transposes to 8.Qd2} (9... Re8 $146 10. O-O-O Be6 11. Qf4
Qd8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Yd7b6,Yb6d5,Gd7f8] The position is balanced.})) 8... Na6 9.
O-O-O (9. Ng3 $2 Bxf4 10. Qxf4 Nb4 11. O-O-O Nxa2+ 12. Kb1 Nb4 $17 {0-1 (39)
Woda,J (2385)-Berg,K (2420) Aabybro 1989}) (9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Ng3 Nc7 $146 11.
Be2 Rd8 12. c3 c5 13. O-O cxd4 {White will play Rfd1 and win back the pawn.
Still Black has a comfortable game, and the preferable position.}) 9... Nb4 10.
Bxd6 Qxd6 11. a3 Nd5 12. Nc3 Re8 $146 {Again the position is balanced.}) 7...
O-O 8. Be2 (8. Qf3 Bxg3 $5 $146 9. hxg3 Qxd4 10. Bd3 h6 11. O-O Re8 $15 {
Thanks to his bishop pair White has some compensation, but only Black can be
better.}) (8. Be3 Re8 9. Qf3 (9. Be2 f5 10. Qd2 Qc7 11. Nh5 Nd7 12. g3 g6 13.
Nf4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gf6e4] Black has a very good game.} 14. f3 Qe7 15. Kf2 g5
16. Nd3 f4 17. gxf4 Nd5 18. Ne5 f6 19. Bc4 gxf4 $1 $146 20. Bxf4 fxe5 21. Rae1
Be6 $19) 9... Be6 10. Bd3 Nd7 11. O-O g6 $5 $146 {Black tries to gain space by
pushing ...c5.} 12. c4 f5 {[%cal Gd8h4,Yc6c5,Rd4d5,Rd7e5]} 13. Bf4 Nf6 $11 {
[%cal Yb7b5]}) (8. Bd3 $6 Re8+ 9. Be3 f5 10. Qh5 $4 (10. Ne2 $146 f4 11. Bd2 f3
12. gxf3 Qh4 $17) 10... g6 $19 {[%cal Gf5f4]}) 8... f5 9. O-O (9. f4 $6 {
This move is very bad positionally. It weakens the squares e3 and e4 and
blocks the c1-bishop.} Re8 10. O-O g6 $5 $146 {[%cal Gb8d7,Yd6f8,Yf8g7,Gb7b5,
Ga7a5,Ga5a4] Over-protection of the f5 pawn, preparing ...Nd7. At some point
Black will play b7-b5 and possibly Bd6-f8-g7, with the better chances.}) 9...
Qh4 $5 $146 {White has a hard time finding a plan.}) 6... Qb6 $5 {I recommend
this rare move, as I believe in today's chess it's important to surprise your
opponent.} (6... Bd6 {is the main move.}) 7. Qc1 (7. Rb1 Be6 $1 $146 8. Bd3
Bxa2 9. Ra1 Qxb2 $1 10. Bd2 Bb4 11. c3 Bxc3 12. Rxa2 Qxa2 13. Bxc3 Nd7 $15 {
Black has three pawns and a rook for the two bishops. Especially the two
queenside passers should give him more than enough compensation.}) (7. Qe2 Bd6
$5 $146 {No reason to be afraid of ghosts or discovered checks!} 8. c3 (8. Bf4+
Kd8 $1 {[%cal Gh8e8]} 9. Bxd6 Re8 10. O-O-O (10. Be5 $2 Qxb2 $1 11. Rd1 fxe5
12. dxe5+ Kc7 $17) 10... Rxe2 11. Nxe2 Be6 {White has some compensation, but
the best he can hope for is a draw.}) 8... O-O 9. Nf3 Re8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f8]
Black has no problems.}) 7... c5 $5 $146 8. Nf3 (8. d5 Bf5 9. Nf3 Be4 10. c4
Bd6 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Nd7 {Black has good control in the center and will
follow-up Rfe8 next. The position is balanced.}) 8... Nc6 9. d5 (9. c3 cxd4 10.
Nxd4 Bc5 11. Nxc6 Qxc6 12. Bxc5 Qxc5 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Bf5 {Black is okay.})
9... Nb4 10. c4 Bf5 11. Nh4 {The only move to stop material losses after ...
Nc2.} Nc2+ 12. Kd1 Be4 13. f3 g5 14. Rb1 $1 (14. fxe4 $6 Nxe3+ 15. Qxe3 Qxb2 $1
{with this intermediate move Black gets the advantage.}) 14... gxh4 15. fxe4
Nxe3+ 16. Qxe3 Bd6 {[%cal Gd6e5] Black's pawn structure may not look pretty,
but the bishop coming to e5 more than compensates for this.} *

