$146 {[%cal Gb2b6]} 12. c4 Bf5 $15 {White has some compensation for the pawn,
but only to fight for equality.}) (11. Qd3 $6 Qa3 $146 12. Qxa3 Bxa3 13. Rab1
b6 $5 $15) (11. c4 Bf8 $146 {Again White's compensation is hardly sufficient.}
12. d5 cxd5 13. cxd5 Nd7 {, with a balanced position.}) 11... Rd8 12. Nd4 Qc3
13. Qf3 Qa5 {, with chances for both sides.}) (7. c3 O-O 8. Be2 Re8 9. O-O Nd7
10. Re1 Nf8 {Black's position is easy to play, as can be seen in the game
Cawdery,D-Li Chao 2017.}) (7. h3 O-O 8. Be2 Re8 9. O-O Nd7 {Here all kind of
moves are possible, such as Re1, Bd3, c3, Be3, c4, but they don't change the
nature of the position.} 10. Bd3 Nf8 11. c4 Ng6 12. Qc2 {Now Black has two
good options:} Qa5 {[%cal Ga5h5,Yc8h3,Gc8e6,Gb7b5]} (12... Bc7 13. Bf5 Qd6 14.
g3 Bxf5 15. Qxf5 Qe6 16. Qxe6 fxe6 17. Be3 Rad8 18. Rfd1 e5 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20.
Nxe5 Bxe5 21. Rab1 {1/2-1/2 (21) Svidler,P (2731)-Berkes,F (2678) Germany 2011}
) 13. c5 Bb8 14. Bd2 Qd8 15. Rfe1 Be6 {with comfortable play. 0-1 (47)
Nepomniachtchi,I (2767)-Carlsen,M (2840) Doha QAT 2016}) (7. Bc4 O-O 8. O-O (8.
Be3 Re8 9. Qd2 Na6 $5 $146 {It's difficult for White to castle long. As could
be seen in previous chapters, Black will have good attacking chances on the
queenside.}) 8... Re8 9. c3 Bg4 10. h3 (10. Qb3 $6 Qc7 $15 {[%csl Rf3,Rh2]}) (
10. Qd3 Nd7 11. Kh1 Qa5 $5 $146 {[%cal Ga5h5] Black is better.}) 10... Bh5 {
It's difficult for White to arrange his pieces with bishop standing on c4. The
pin h5-d1 is unpleasant.} 11. Be2 Nd7 12. Re1 Nb6 $146 {[%cal Gd6c7,Gd8d6] ,
and Black has no problems.}) (7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 (8. Bd3 Re8 9. Qd2 {White
wants to castle long. But this is dubious:} Na6 $1 $146 {We already saw this
idea a couple of times.} 10. c3 (10. O-O $6 Nb4 $1 {Black gets the initiative.}
11. Be2 Bf5 12. c3 Nc2 13. Rac1 Nxe3 14. fxe3 Qe7 $17) (10. O-O-O $2 Nb4 11. a3
Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 Be6 $17 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 10... Nc7 $15 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gc7d5]
Black will very soon threaten to win the bishop pair.}) 8... Re8 {It's
important to wait for White's next move. In case of 0-0-0 Black wants to keep
the option ...Na6 at his disposal.} 9. O-O-O Be6 {Preventing d4-d5.} 10. Kb1
Na6 $1 $146 {Black has the advantage.}) (7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. Re1 (9. c3 {
transposes to 7.c3}) (9. h3 {transposes to 7.h3}) (9. c4 Nd7 10. Bd3 Nf8 11. h3
{once again this transposes to 7.h3.}) (9. Be3 Nd7 10. c4 Nf8 11. Qd2 (11. c5
$6 Bc7 12. b4 Be6 $1 {[%cal Ge6d5]} 13. b5 Bd5 14. a4 Ne6 $146 {[%cal Gd8d7,
