Nxf4 34. bxc5 Nxe2 35. Na7 Rde5 {0-1 (35) Janik,I (2422)-Svane,R (2587) Batumi
GEO 2018}) 8... Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5 $5 {The starting point for the critical test of
this repertoire. In this chapter we will look at lines in which White castles
kingside.} 10. O-O (10. h3 Nd7 11. O-O (11. Be3 Nf8 12. O-O-O {transposes to
chapter 8.}) 11... Nf8 12. a4 $6 {This move doesn't make sense.} Bc7 13. Re1 h4
14. Be3 g5 $5 $146 {[%cal Gf8e6,Ge6g7,Gd8d6] Black is slightly better already.}
) 10... h4 {I like the idea ...h5 and ...h4, which takes away the square g3
from White's knight. Later Black can continue Bc7 and Qd6 in order to force
weaknesses on White's kingside. disturb White on the kingside or play the
usual maneuver ...Nd7-f8. One might wonder how to follow up Ng6, but firstly
