f-pawn is going to be pushed forward, making it difficult for White to do
without this undesirable move.} f5 {The position is balanced.}) 14... Qc7 15.
Bf4 Rxe2 16. Bxc7 Rxc2 17. Bxb8 Rxb2 {If Black had played 13...Bc7, White's
bishop would not be under attack now and Re8 would lead to a winning position.}
18. Bd6 Bd7 {White has enough compensation for the pawn, but no more than that.
}) (13. Rad1 {Probably the most challenging move which was played only once by
Abdumalik,Z. This continuation is much more flexible than 13.c4. The rook will
occupy the d1-square in any case. On the other hand, depending on the concrete
circumstances, White can decide whether to go for c3-c4 or not. For example,
if Black wants to transpose to 13.c4 by playing 13...Bb8, instead of playing
14.c4, White can keep improving his position with the simple 14.Rfe1. Black's
most difficult task in this position is bringing the c8-bishop and a8-rook
into the game.} Bd7 $5 $146 {This is a new idea. Black prepares ...Qc8 on the
