his king will be safe on the queenside.} 13. Re1 e6 {[%cal Ge8c8]} 14. Ne5
O-O-O 15. Bf4 Bd6 $11 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Yh8h5]}) 8... e6 9. c3 Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6]
, and Black has no problems.}) (6. h4 Bg4 7. Be2 (7. d4 c5 {transposes to
chapter 3.}) 7... e6 8. d3 Nbd7 9. Ng5 Qc7 10. Bd2 (10. Bxg4 hxg4 11. Qe2 Bb4+
$5 $146 {Provoking c2-c3, which makes queenside castling less safe for White.}
12. c3 Be7 {Black is okay.}) 10... Bxe2 $146 11. Qxe2 Qe5 12. Qxe5 Nxe5 {
Black is fine.}) 6... h4 7. Nf1 (7. Ng5 $2 hxg3 8. Bxf7+ Kd7 9. Be6+ Kc7 10. d4
gxf2+ $1 $146 11. Kxf2 Ne4+ $19) (7. Ne5 $6 e6 8. Ne2 b5 $146 9. Bb3 c5 10. d3
h3 $17) (7. Ne2 h3 8. gxh3 (8. Ne5 $2 e6 9. g3 $2 b5 $146 10. Bb3 c5 $19 {
[%csl Re5][%cal Gc8b7,Gd8c7,Gb7h1]}) (8. g3 $2 b5 9. Bb3 c5 $17 {[%cal Gc8b7]})
8... b5 $5 $146 {A tricky move. To stay in the game, White needs to play Bd3,
as Bb3 can be answered with ...c5 and ...Bb7 again.} 9. Bd3 Bb7 {[%cal Ge7e6,
