Nxe6 (18. b4 Nd5 $17) 18... Nxe6 19. Bxe6 Bc5 20. d4 Rhe8 21. dxc5 Rxe6 {
Black enjoys the initiative as his bishop has better perspectives.}) 9. b3
Qxe3+ 10. fxe3 a5 11. a4 Bf5 12. d3 f6 13. Bb2 e5 {Black is okay.}) 7... Qe6+ (
7... Bf5 {The more solid alternative. Black refuses to hunt for pawns and
instead calmly develops.} 8. Bc4 Qd6 9. d3 e6 10. Bf4 $1 (10. Bd2 Nd7 $5 $146 {
Waiting for White to castle, in order to follow-up Be7 and exchange of queens.
This way White's king is further away from the centre and his rook on h1 is
not activated immediately.} 11. O-O Be7 12. Qg3 Qxg3 13. hxg3 $11) (10. O-O Be7
11. Bg5 Bxg5 12. Qxg5 O-O 13. Nh4 Bg6 14. Nxg6 hxg6 {Black had no problem in
the following game:} 15. Rae1 Nd7 16. Re3 Nb6 17. Bb3 a5 18. a4 Nd5 19. Re4
Rfe8 20. Rfe1 Rad8 21. Qd2 b6 22. Re5 Qb4 23. Qd1 Qd6 24. d4 Nf6 25. c3 c5 26.
dxc5 Qxe5 27. Rxe5 Rxd1+ 28. Bxd1 Rd8 29. Bf3 Nd7 30. Re1 Nxc5 31. Rd1 Rc8 32.
Rd4 e5 33. Rc4 Rd8 34. h3 f5 35. b4 axb4 36. Rxb4 Rd6 37. a5 bxa5 38. Rb5 Nd3
39. Rxa5 e4 40. Be2 Nf4 41. Kf1 Kh7 42. Ra2 Rb6 43. Rd2 Rb1+ 44. Rd1 Rb2 45.
Re1 g5 46. Bd1 Rb1 47. Bc2 Rxe1+ 48. Kxe1 Nxg2+ 49. Ke2 Kg6 50. f3 e3 51. c4
Kf6 52. c5 f4 53. Be4 Ke5 54. Kd3 Nh4 55. Kc2 Nf5 56. Kc3 Nd4 {0-1 (56) Supi,L
(2548) -Howell,D (2689) Batumi GEO 2018}) 10... Qe7 $5 $146 (10... Qb4+ $6 11.
c3 $1 $146 (11. Bd2 Qd6) 11... Qe7 (11... Qxb2 12. O-O $16 {Black cannot
afford being this far behind in development.}) 12. Qg3 Nd7 13. Nd4 $16) 11. Qg3
Nd7 12. Nd4 Bg6 13. O-O Nf6 14. Be5 $1 (14. Rfe1 Nh5 15. Qf3 Nxf4 16. Qxf4
O-O-O $1 {Black is okay.}) 14... Nd7 15. Bf4 Nf6 16. Be5 Nd7 17. Bc7 Qf6 18. c3
(18. Nf3 Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 19. Rfe1 O-O {solves Black's problems.}) 18... Bc5
(18... Be7 $2 19. Rfe1 $16 {[%cal Gd4e6,Gc4e6]}) 19. Nf3 O-O 20. d4 Be7 21.
Rfe1 Bh5 22. Ne5 Nxe5 23. Bxe5 Qg6 24. Qe3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f5] White has some
pressure thanks to his space advantage.}) 8. Be2 Qg6 9. O-O Qxc2 {As it was
already mentioned, this is a very risky variation. But if Black knows what to
do, it can also become very risky for White, who needs to calculate very well
to keep his compensation alive.} 10. Bc4 Qf5 11. Re1 e6 12. d4 Nd7 13. Qg3 (13.
Ne5 Be7 14. Qg3 O-O {Black already has nothing to worry about.}) (13. Bg5 $5 {
[%cal Gd4d5,Gf3d4] This is a very tricky move. White threatens to push d4-d5.}
Nb6 14. d5 $5 (14. Bb3 f6 15. Bd2 Be7 (15... Bd6 16. d5 $5 Nxd5 17. Nd4 Qd3 18.
Rad1 g5 19. Bxg5 $1 fxg5 20. Qg4 $1 e5 $1 21. Qxc8+ Rxc8 22. Rxd3 Kf7 23. Nf3
g4 24. Nxe5+ Bxe5 25. Rxe5 Rhe8 26. Rxe8 Rxe8 27. Kf1 Re5 $11) 16. d5 Nxd5 17.
