{[#] This structure is very important for the variation with 4...Nf6. Let's
try to make some general considerations. From a structural point of view,
White has an advantage since Black has doubled pawns on the f-file. Also,
White enjoys a considerable space advantage in the center. On the other hand,
Black's position is extremely solid. The doubled pawns on the f-file are not
as weak as they may seem. The f6-pawn does useful work. By taking the control
over the important e5 -square, this pawn restricts White's f3-knight. In some
positions, also white light-squared bishop can be constrained by the f6-pawn.
As a general observation, we can say that White has difficulties to find good
squares for his minor pieces. If White manages to exchange all minor pieces,
the endgames with heavy pieces should be favorable for him because of the
possibility to create a passed pawn along the d-file. On the other hand, White
should be careful when exchanging pieces since every exchange reduces the
impact of the space advantage. In positions with heavy pieces and only one
minor piece on the board, Black can put pressure on the d4-pawn. Besides
creating a passed pawn along the d-file, White can also go for the advance
c4-c5. This advance is good only when it is followed by d4-d5. Otherwise,
Black can make use of the weak d5-square, as we are going to witness in the
next game. Now, let's see what Black wants to achieve in this structure. His
most problematic piece is the light-squared bishop which disturbs the
coordination of the heavy pieces. That is why Black usually tries to relocate
this bishop to e4 or exchange it. The exchange of the light-squared bishops is
generally favorable for Black. In general, if the light-squared bishop is
exchanged for the knight, then Black can also consider trading the
dark-squared bishops. In positions in which Black has queen and knight against
the queen and light-squared bishop, the pressure on d4 can be an issue for
White. Another typical option for Black is to carry out the b7-b5 advance. The
idea is to provoke the move c4-c5 after which Black can install his knight on
the weak d5-square. In some cases, the advance c6-c5 can also be an option.
The point is that the d4-pawn controls the important e5-square which can be
used as a regrouping base for black pieces. If White answers c6-c5 with d4-d5,
then his bishops will remain passive for a long time. Before playing c6-c5,
Black must be sure that the blockade on d6 is viable. Sometimes, in this
structure, Black can also go for active actions on the kingside. The pressure
along the e-file can be combined with a Q+B battery along the h2-b8 diagonal.
In some positions, even bishop sacrifices on h3 are possible.} 14... a5 $5 {
This is an excellent positional decision. Gaining space on the queenside is a
part of Black's strategy. Under favorable circumstances, Black wants to play
a5-a4 and b7-b5. Of course, White can sustain the c4-pawn by means of b2-b3.
In this case, however, there will be massive exchanges on the queenside. The
general positional rule says that we should always exchange pawns on the wing
where our opponent has a pawn majority.} 15. a3 {Even though the computer
likes this move, from a human perspective, this is not a good decision. In
this structure, Black can fix White's queenside pawns by means of a5-a4. Later
on, White cannot answer b7-b5 with b2-b3. In this way, Black will take the
d5-square under control.} ({Another option would have been} 15. Bd3 a4 16. Rad1
{White goes for centralization and keeps all the options open. In this
position, Black can play} Qd7 {[%cal Gd6c7,Gd7d6] With this move, Black
discloses his intentions on the kingside. Now, the idea ...Bc7 followed by ...
Qd6 becomes possible. At the same time, in some lines, the bishop sacrifice on
h3 would be an issue. For example, the idea} 17. Ne5 $5 fxe5 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19.
Bxh7+ Kh8 20. c5 {runs into} Bxh3 $1 {when the position remains unclear since
the h3 - bishop is untouchable.} 21. gxh3 $4 Qxh3 22. Be4 Nf3+ 23. Bxf3 Bh2+
24. Kh1 Qxf3+ 25. Kxh2 Re5 {[%cal Ge5h5] with a mate to follow.}) 15... Qd7 {
Once again, we see the multi-functional move.} (15... a4 {is also possible.})
16. Bf1 Bf5 $5 {As we have already pointed out, the idea to transfer the
bishop to e4 is typical for this pawn structure. Very often the move ...Be4
works very well with the sequence ...Bc7 followed by ...Qd6. The Q+B battery
is very effective when the f3-knight is under pressure.} 17. Qc3 ({White
should be very careful when playing moves like} 17. Bd3 $2 {Now, the typical}
Bxh3 $1 $17 {works very well for Black. If White takes the bishop, the attack
is unstoppable. For instance:} 18. gxh3 $2 Qxh3 {[%csl Rf3,Rg1] Now, White is
unable to protect his f3-knight. The position is simply winning for Black.} 19.
Be4 (19. Qe2 Nh4 20. Nxh4 Qh2+ 21. Kf1 Qh1#) 19... Qg4+ 20. Kf1 Rxe4 $19) 17...
a4 {Now, the drawback of the move a2-a3 becomes clear. Objectively speaking,
the position remains balanced. Nevertheless, every strong player would take
Black here since White does not have a constructive plan.} 18. Rad1 {Standard
move allows Black to proceed with his strategy.} ({An interesting option would
have been} 18. b4 $5 {Even though this move destroys White's pawn structure,
it can change the nature of the position since White has some piece play along
with the b-file.} axb3 19. Qxb3 Be4 {The bishop occupies the perfect e4-square
just in time.} ({A typical mistake would have been} 19... Re7 $6 {With the
black rook being on e7, White can go for the c4-c5 advance. In this case,
Black does not have the maneuver Ng6-e7-d5. Here is how the game may continue:}
20. a4 Be4 21. Nd2 Bf5 22. c5 $1 (22. Nf3 Be4 23. Nd2 Bf5 24. Nf3 $11) 22...
Bc7 23. Nc4 {[%csl Rb7] White's pressure against the b7-pawn is very annoying.
Now, Black should care about equality.}) 20. Nd2 Bf5 21. c5 (21. Nf3 $11) 21...
Bc7 22. Nc4 Be6 23. a4 f5 {[%cal Gf5f4,Gg6h4,Ge6d5] Black has the initiative
on the kingside.}) 18... Bc7 $1 19. Qc1 Qd6 {Maybe this is not the most
precise move order.} ({Better would have been} 19... Be4 $1 20. Nd2 Qd6 21. g3
Bf5 $15 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] In this position, Black is clearly better. After
provoking the g2-g3 advance, he can consider further weakening White's
position by means of the advance h7-h5-h4.}) 20. c5 {Without this move, White
does not have any counterplay.} ({The move} 20. Bd3 {is well met by} Bxd3 21.
Rxd3 Ne5 $1 {This thematic reaction works very well when White's pieces are
not coordinated. Black changes the pawn structure in a favorable way.} 22. Nxe5
fxe5 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Ge5e4,Gd6h2]} 23. g3 Qg6 $1 24. Rdd1 h5 $1 25. h4 exd4
26. Rxd4 (26. Bxd4 $4 Bxg3 27. fxg3 Qxg3+ 28. Kh1 Qxh4+ 29. Kg2 Rxe1 30. Rxe1
Qxd4 $19) 26... Be5 27. Rd2 Bf6 $15 {[%csl Rb2] Black is better due to his
more active pieces and White's numerous weaknesses. Once again we see the
importance of the a4-pawn.}) 20... Qd8 ({Another option is} 20... Qd7 $5 21. d5
$1 {A thematic idea in this structure. White sacrifices a pawn in order to
free the d4-square for his knight.} cxd5 22. Nd4 {[%cal Gf1b5]} Ne5 23. Bb5 Nc6
24. Bf4 Be6 {White's compensation is probably sufficient for equality.}) 21. d5
$1 {Once again, we see this typical pawn sacrifice. We should keep this idea
in mind in our games.} (21. Bc4 Be6 $1 $15 {After exchanging the light-squared
bishops, Black wants to maneuver his knight to d5. We will see this pattern
later in the article.}) 21... cxd5 22. Nd4 $2 {This move allows Black to
consolidate his position by 22...Bd7.} ({White should have played} 22. Bb5 $1 {
when after} Re7 23. Nd4 {is very strong.} Be6 (23... Bc8 $5 {This move is
possible as well. Later Black will try to play ...Ne5 followed by ...Ra5.
Nevertheless, White has a very nice compensation.}) 24. Nxe6 Rxe6 25. Rd4 Be5
26. Rxa4 Rxa4 27. Bxa4 Qa5 28. b3 (28. Bb3 Bxb2 $15) 28... Bc3 29. b4 (29. Rd1
d4 $19 {Black gets the initiative.}) 29... Bxb4 30. axb4 Qxa4 $15 {It seems
that White does not have a sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 22... Bd7 $1
$17 {Now, Black's advantage is out of question.} 23. Nb5 Bc6 24. Nxc7 Qxc7 25.
Qc3 Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5] Black rightly decides to improve the position of his
knight.} ({The moves} 25... Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6] and}) (25... Re6 {[%cal Ga8e8]
are interesting as well.}) 26. Bc1 Re6 (26... Nf5 $17) 27. Rxe6 $2 {This is a
very strange decision. Now, Black's central pawns are unstoppable.} fxe6 28.
Qb4 Ng6 29. f4 e5 $19 {And Black went on to win.} 30. fxe5 fxe5 31. Be2 Qe7 32.
Bg4 Rd8 33. Re1 h6 34. Qc3 d4 35. Qc4+ Bd5 36. Qc2 Nh4 37. Qe2 e4 38. Bf4 {
Cawdery,D - Li Chao 0-1 , 2017} *

