{[#] The knowledge of this structure is very important for everyone who wants
to play the line 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4 Nf6. The advance c4-c5
gives White a lot of space but weakens the d5-square. Moreover, White must
always pay attention to the backward d4-pawn. Let's take a look at the plans
of both sides. Plans for White: 1) carry out the d4-d5 advance. In this case
White obtains a powerful queenside pawn majority and firm control over the
d-file. 2) d4-d5 pawn sacrifice in order to free the d4-square for the knight.
This important positional idea allows White to improve his worst piece - the
f3-knight 3) exchange the dark-squared bishops and install a knight on d6. In
such a case the powerful d6-knight would dominate the position. Nevertheless,
this plan is very time-consuming and practically impossible to carry out. 4)
play b2-b4-b5-bxc6 and penetrate via b-file. This plan is very natural since
White has a space advantage on the queenside. The main drawback is that this
idea is very slow. Plans for Black: 1) exchange light-squared bishops and
install a knight on d5. This is by far the most typical plan for Black. After
putting his knight on d5, Black usually goes for active actions on the
kingside. 2) exchange pieces and put pressure on the d4-pawn. Of course,
exchanges reduce the impact of the opponent's space advantage. In every
endgame. the d4-pawn would become a weakness. Nevertheless, practice shows
that Black can hardly play for a win if he does not create a second weakness
in White's camp. Now, let's take a look at the game Nepomniachti, I - Carlsen,
M. In this position, the World Champion settled for an exchange of the
light-squared bishops.} 18... Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Qd7 20. b4 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gb4b5]
White is going for a queenside expansion. As we have already explained, his
idea is to open the b-file by means of a2-a4 followed by b4-b5 and bxc6.} Ng6
$1 {[%cal Gg6e7,Ge7d5] Just in time! The knight is heading for the d5-square.}
21. a4 Ne7 22. b5 Nd5 {[%csl Rd2,Gd5] The knight is dominating the entire
board. The classical positional theory affirms that when you have a powerful
knight in the center, you should attack the wing where you are stronger. That
is why Black should now go for a kingside expansion. Also, one should pay
attention to the useless d2-bishop which is entirely dominated by the knight.
At the same time, the f3-knight is restricted by the f6-pawn.} 23. bxc6 bxc6
24. Qa6 {As it happens very often in this structure, White's queenside play
turns out to be very slow.} g5 $1 {[%cal Gg8h8,Gg5g4] Black starts his
kingside attack. He can follow with ...Kh8 and g5-g4, thus opening the g-file
with a mating attack.} 25. Nh2 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gh2g4,Gh2f1,Gf1e3,Gg4e3] White
stops the advance g5-g4 and intends to exchange the powerful black knight via
the e3-square.} Bxh2+ $1 {This is a very strong positional decision. Now, we
have a classic case of a good knight against a bad bishop. After parting with
his bishop, Black will not play for a mating attack anymore. Since White does
not have any real counterplay, Black can maneuver and combine threats on both
wings.} 26. Kxh2 Kg7 {This is a mistake after which Carlsen takes control over
the b-file.} 27. Kg1 $2 ({More tenacious would have been} 27. Qd3 {White is
centralizing the queen and is taking the control over the b1-square in order
to fight for the b-file in a case of necessity.} Rab8 (27... Rxe1 28. Rxe1 Rb8
29. Rb1 $15) 28. Rxe8 Rxe8 29. Rb1 h6 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd5e7,Ge7f5,Ye8d8,
Ye7g6] It is known that after blockading the backward (or isolated) pawn, we
should find a way to attack it. In the particular position, Black can prepare
the attack with simple moves such as Ne7-f5 followed by Rd8. White is doomed
to passivity.}) 27... Rxe1+ 28. Rxe1 Rb8 $17 {[%csl Gb8,Re1] In this position,
the b-file is a way more important than the e-file. White doesn't have
penetration squares along the e-file. On the other hand, Black is ready to
enter White's camp.} 29. Qd3 Rb2 $1 30. a5 h6 {Black overprotects the g5-pawn
and frees more space for the king.} 31. Bc1 $2 {This move allows black rook
the remain in White's camp.} ({A better try was} 31. Rb1 {when Black should
play} Qb7 ({The idea} 31... Ra2 {don't work anymore since White invades
Black's camp via the b-file. For instance, after} 32. a6 f5 33. Rb7 Qe8 34. f3
$1 Ra1+ 35. Kh2 f4 36. Qe4 $1 {White is pretty much in the game.}) 32. Rxb2
Qxb2 $17 {Black's advantage is obvious, but White still has chances to hold
this position.}) 31... Ra2 32. Bd2 Qb7 $1 {[%cal Gb7b2] The queen is heading
for the b2-square. Black's position is already winning.} 33. Re8 (33. Rb1 $4
Rxd2 $19) (33. Rd1 Qb2 $17) 33... Qb2 $19 34. Be1 Nf4 35. Qa6 Qxd4 $6 {This
was not the most precise decision from a technical point of view.} ({Better was
} 35... Ra1 $142 $1 36. Qc8 Ng6 $19 {[%csl Rd4,Re1,Rg1,Gg6,Gg7][%cal Gb2d2,
Ra1g1] with an easy win.}) 36. Qc8 Ng6 37. Qxc6 $6 {White misses his last
chance.} ({He should have played} 37. Rg8+ $1 {This calculation of this move
is difficult even for a classical time control.In a rapid game, it's
understandable that Ian missed that. Even this move, however, doesn't solve
the problems. Here are some lines:} Kh7 38. Rxg6 $3 Kxg6 (38... fxg6 39. Qe6 $1
Ra1 40. Qf7+ Kh8 41. Qf8+ Kh7 42. Qf7+ $11) 39. Qg8+ Kf5 40. Qc8+ Ke4 41. Qxc6+
Kd3 42. Qf3+ Kc4 43. c6 $1 Ra1 44. Qe2+ Kb3 45. c7 Rc1 46. Qe7 Qc3 47. c8=Q
Rxe1+ $1 (47... Qxc8 $2 48. Qb4+ Ka2 49. Qa4+ Kb2 50. Qb4+ $11) 48. Qxe1 Qxe1+
49. Kh2 Qxf2 50. a6 $17) 37... Ra1 $19 38. Qe4 Qxc5 39. Kh2 h5 40. Qe3 Qc6 41.
Bc3 Ra4 42. f3 Ra2 43. Kh1 Rc2 44. Be1 Qb5 45. Bg3 h4 46. Bh2 Qb1+ 47. Bg1 Qf1
{Nepomniachtchi,I - Carlsen,M 0-1 , 2016 , Rapid.} *

