{Sometimes, the white king is not entirely safe even on the kingside. Let's
take a look at the position on the diagram which was reached in the game
Bracker,F (2392) -Voigt, M (2346) Germany GER 2018. First of all, it is
important to mention that the e2-square is considered to be the best place for
the white knight in this structure. As we have already seen, the f3-square is
not optimal since the f6-pawn would restrict the knight. On the other hand,
being on e2, the knight has access to the important squares g3 and f4. In
order to take the g3-square under control, Black often plays h7-h5-h4, as it
was the case in the current game. The h4-pawn gives Black a lot of space as
well. As we are going to witness, the position of the white knight on e2
implies some risks.. Since White does not control the h2-square, the typical
Q+B battery along the b8-h2 diagonal may become very dangerous. In the game,
White played} 13. Bf5 $6 {This is a positional mistake. As we have already
pointed out, Black has problems to find a good square for his c8-bishop. That
is why White's decision to exchange it doesn't make a lot of sense. Moreover,
White wastes a lot of time and Black can build his attacking strategy.} ({
A better decision would have been} 13. c4 {In this case, Black should decide
how to build the battery. There are two reasonable moves 13...Bc7 and 13...Bb8.
In this position, I prefer} Bb8 $5 $146 {which is also a novelty. The
following variation demonstrates the difference between the two bishop moves.}
14. Rfe1 ({Bad is} 14. Rad1 $2 {in view of} Qc7 15. Bf4 Rxe2 $1 {A thematic
idea for this pawn structure.} 16. Bxc7 Rxc2 17. Bxb8 Rxb2 $17 {Black is
almost winning.}) 14... Qc7 15. Bf4 Rxe2 16. Bxc7 Rxc2 17. Bxb8 Rxb2 {The idea
of 13...Bb8 becomes clear. Had Black played 13...Bc7, now White's bishop
wouldn't have been under attack. In such a case, White has played 18. Re8 with
a winning position.} 18. Bd6 Bd7 {Black is a pawn up but White's bishop pair
and strong center give him enough compensation. The position remains balanced.}
) 13... Bc7 14. Bxc8 Rxc8 15. Qd2 $2 {Another pointless move which leads to a
lost position.} ({Probably, White should have opted for} 15. Qf5 {Even in this
case, however, Black is better. The game may continue} g6 16. Qf3 Ne6 $15 {
[%cal Gd8d6,Gf6f5] Black's play is very easy. He can follow with . ..Qd6 and ..
.f6-f5.}) 15... Qd6 16. f4 {With a knight on e2 and a bishop on e3, this move
is a huge concession. Now, White's minor pieces are very passive while the
e-file is seriously weakened.} (16. Bf4 $4 Rxe2 $19) 16... Re4 {[%cal Gc8e8]}
17. Rf3 Rce8 18. Kf2 Nd7 {[%cal Gf6f5,Gd7f6] Black improves his last passive
piece. He is planning to play ...f6-f5 followed by ...Nf6. Black's position is
already winning.} 19. c4 f5 20. g4 Nf6 21. g5 Ng4+ {0-1 (21) Bracker,F (2392)
-Voigt, M (2346) Germany GER 2018} *

