[PlyCount "21"]
[EventDate "2018.10.25"]

{[#] Generally speaking, in this pawn structure, White's plan based on the
long castle is very risky. Given the fact that Black has four pawns on the
kingside (versus three white pawns), a possible pawn storm wouldn't be a good
strategy for White. He must settle for a piece attack, trying to exploit the
weakening move h7-h5. Black has more than one way to put pressure on White's
king. Below, you can find some of the possible strategies: 1) launching a pawn
storm on the queenside by means of b7-b5, a7-a5, and b5-b4. The idea is to
open files against the white king. 2) gaining space on the queenside by
playing b7-b5 and a7-a5-a4. Later on Black can transfer his queen to the
d5-square. Note that the Q+B battery along the a2-g8 diagonal can be very
dangerous 3) opening up the position by means of c6-c5 and going for a piece
of play. This strategy works very well when White's pieces are poorly
coordinated. Now let's see one of the ideas we have in our pack. In general,
in this pawn structure, c3-d4 pawns against c6 and King is on the Queenside,
our main idea was to play b5-a5-a4 and of course ...Qd5 at some moment.(which
you saw in our files). Here we will see one more nice idea.} 16... Nxe3 $5 {
With this move, Black is planning to open the position by playing c6-c5 on the
next move. This idea is justified by the fact that black pieces are much more
active.} ({Another option would have been} 16... Bf8 {[%cal Gd5b6,Ga5d5]
followed by ...Nb6 and ...Qd5.}) 17. fxe3 c5 $1 {Black tries to open up the
position to make use of his very well placed pieces. We should keep in mind
that even ideas like ...cxd4 followed by Bxa3 are very interesting. Very often,
Black's rooks can be transferred to the queenside via 5th and 6th ranks.} 18.
c4 $6 {This move weakens the structure.} ({An interesting position arises after
} 18. Nxd6 Rxd6 19. Rhf1 Kf8 $1 $15 {This is a very deep move. Black doesn't
go for immediate actions on the queenside but prepares all his forces. The
idea of Black's last move is to protect the e8-rook! When the rook is
protected, Black can open the e-file by playing cxd4. Later on, the attack can
follow with ...Qd5 and ...Rb6. One might say that the move 19...Kf8 is not so
useful but let's take a look at some lines.} (19... cxd4 20. exd4 Rb6 {[%cal
Ga5a3]} ({Another option is} 20... Qd5 21. Rf5 {[%csl Re8] This move would not
be possible if the rook is protected.} Qa2+ 22. Kc1 Rc8 23. Rxh5 Rxd4 24. Bh7+
Kf8 25. Qe2 {The position is complicated.}) 21. Rf5 $5 {Once again, the same
idea.} Qxa3 22. d5 Bd7 23. Rxe8+ Bxe8 24. Rxh5 {With a very unclear position.})
) 18... cxd4 19. Nxd6 $2 {This is a huge mistake. Now, the black rook enters
the attack via the 6th rank.} ({More tenacious would have been.} 19. exd4 {
Even in this case, however, Black can go for his thematic sacrifice} Bxa3 $1
20. bxa3 Rxd4 {Black has more than enough compensation for the piece - two
pawns and weak white king. In such positions, Black does not need a forced win
since the white monarch will be vulnerable in the long term.} 21. Re3 ({
An interesting try would be} 21. Rd1 b5 $5 22. Nd6 ({The endgame arising after
} 22. Qc3 Qxc3 23. Nxc3 Rxd3 24. Rxd3 Bf5 25. Kb2 Bxd3 26. cxb5 a6 $17 {
Is close to lost for White.}) 22... Rxd6 23. Bh7+ Kh8 24. Rxd6 bxc4 {[%csl Rb1]
[%cal Ge8b8,Gc4c3] It seems that White is on the verge of losing since Black
is planning to follow with Rb8 and c4-c3. Nevertheless, White has a remarkable
defence at his disposal.} 25. Ka2 $3 c3+ 26. Rxe6 Rxe6 27. Bd3 Qd5+ 28. Ka1 g6
$15 {Black's play is still easier due to the vulnerable white king.} 29. Qxc3
$4 Rc6 $19) 21... b5 22. Qc3 Qxc3 23. Nxc3 Rxd3 24. Rxd3 Bf5 $17) 19... Rxd6
20. e4 (20. exd4 Rxd4 $19) 20... Rc8 21. Qe2 Rb6 22. Ka1 Rb3 23. Qc2 Rxa3+ 24.
bxa3 Qxa3+ 25. Kb1 Rc6 26. c5 Rxc5 {Bernotas, A - Berkes,F 0-1 , 2018} *

