{This position seems to be favorable for White. In the endgame, he practically
has an extra pawn due to Black's doubled f-pawns. Nevertheless, the position
of the white king gives Black some resources.} 13... c5 $5 {Black should play
very energetically in order not to find himself in a passive position without
counterplay.} 14. Rhe1 $6 (14. dxc5 $146 Nc6 {[%cal Ga8d8]} 15. Rae1 Ne5 16.
Bb5 Rec8 {[%cal Gc8c5] Black is doing fine. I think White should not allow
Black to take on ...Rc5. For that reason:} 17. c6 $1 {This slows down Black's
initiative.} (17. f3 Rxc5 18. Be2 b5 $1 {Black has an easy game with.}) 17...
bxc6 18. Be2 c5 {[%cal Gc5c4] I believe our activity will compensate our pawn
structure.}) (14. Nd5 $146 cxd4 15. cxd4 (15. Nc7 $2 dxc3+ 16. Kxc3 Rc8 17.
Nxa8 b5 $17 {[%csl Ra8,Rc3,Rc4][%cal Gb8d7,Gd7e5]}) 15... Nd7 16. Rhe1 (16. Nc7
$2 Rac8 17. Nxe8 Rxc4 $17 {[%csl Re8]}) 16... Red8 {Black has good pressure on
center.}) 14... Rd8 $1 $146 {This move puts more pressure on the center.} 15.
d5 g5 $1 {Black starts playing against the d5-pawn.} 16. Nh5 Nd7 {[%csl Rd5]
[%cal Gd7b6]} 17. Ng3 Bg6 {[%cal Gd7b6]} 18. Bf1 c4 $5 $17 {[%csl Rd2,Gd3,Rd5]
[%cal Gb7b5,Gd7c5,Gd7e5] Black is already clearly better. He may follow with ..
.b7-b5 and ...Nc5 or ...Ne5, depending on the position.} *

